<Base title="Methodology" compactHeader={true} toc={toc}>
  <p class="ar-title" lang="ar" dir="rtl">المنهج</p>
  <h2>Methodology</h2>
  <p class="summary">How Dār al-Ḥaqq evaluates contested claims, the hierarchy of sources we draw on, and the technical vocabulary every visitor should know before reading the topic pages.</p>

  <h3 id="evaluation">How a claim is evaluated on this site</h3>
  <p>Every contested question on this site goes through the same four-step evaluation:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>The Salafī position is presented first, in its own terms,</strong> with a representative quotation from a recognized Salafī source (Ibn Taymiyya, Ibn ʿAbd al-Wahhāb, Albānī, Ibn Bāz, Ibn al-ʿUthaymīn, or contemporary Salafī Q&amp;A sites such as IslamQA.info).</li>
    <li><strong>The classical Sunnī position is presented next,</strong> drawn from one or more of the four madhāhib (Ḥanafī, Mālikī, Shāfiʿī, Ḥanbalī) and from the Ashʿarī or Māturīdī ʿaqīdah literature, with at least one verbatim citation.</li>
    <li><strong>The textual basis on each side is laid out</strong> — Qurʾānic verses, ḥadīth, and the uṣūl al-fiqh principles each side reasons from. The same passages are read differently by the two camps; the page makes the hermeneutic difference explicit rather than asserting one reading and dismissing the other.</li>
    <li><strong>A respectful but pointed evaluation of the Salafī position closes the page,</strong> naming the specific methodological problems, internal inconsistencies, and departures from the Salaf the position claims to follow. Where the Salafī tradition's stated principle and its operative practice come apart, where its reading of a text produces conclusions the classical schools do not, where the position has not yet articulated a coherent reply to specific classical objections — these are surfaced rather than smoothed over. The framing remains scholarly: the position is named, the position is engaged, the reader is given enough to weigh the matter themselves.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>The aim is not to score points but to give the reader enough to make their own informed judgement, and to know what their sources are when they go to study the question further.</p>

  <h3 id="sources">Source hierarchy</h3>
  <p>In Sunnī uṣūl al-fiqh, the recognized sources of a religious ruling are, in order:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>The Qurʾān</strong> — the literal Word of Allāh, transmitted by uninterrupted mass-narration (<em>tawātur</em>).</li>
    <li><strong>The Sunnah</strong> — the recorded sayings, actions, and tacit approvals of the Prophet ﷺ, transmitted through ḥadīth literature graded by isnād authenticity (<em>ṣaḥīḥ</em>, <em>ḥasan</em>, <em>ḍaʿīf</em>).</li>
    <li><strong>Ijmāʿ</strong> — the consensus of the qualified scholars of a generation on a question.</li>
    <li><strong>Qiyās</strong> — analogical reasoning extending a Qurʾānic or Sunnah ruling to a parallel new case.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>All four schools (Ḥanafī, Mālikī, Shāfiʿī, Ḥanbalī) accept these four. The schools differ on subordinate sources: <em>istiḥsān</em> (juristic preference, prominent in Ḥanafī fiqh), <em>maṣlaḥa mursala</em> (unrestricted public interest, prominent in Mālikī fiqh), and <em>ʿamal ahl al-Madīna</em> (the practice of the people of Medina, distinctively Mālikī).</p>
  <p>The Salafī methodological claim is that they restrict themselves to "the Qurʾān and the Sunnah upon the understanding of the Salaf" and that the four-madhāhib structure adds unnecessary intermediation. The classical reply is that the four schools <em>are</em> the codified understanding of the Salaf, refined over generations by scholars whose isnāds in fiqh, ḥadīth, and ʿaqīdah trace back through the Salaf themselves. The disagreement is real, and the topic pages on this site work it out case by case.</p>

  <h3 id="glossary">Glossary of key terms</h3>

  <p class="term"><strong>Bidʿah</strong> — Innovation. Linguistically, anything new. Technically, a religious practice or belief introduced after the time of the Prophet ﷺ that has no basis in the established Sharīʿah. The Salafī position holds that <em>every</em> bidʿah is misguidance (<em>kullu bidʿatin ḍalālah</em>); the classical Sunnī position, going back to ʿUmar ibn al-Khaṭṭāb's reaction to congregational tarāwīḥ ("<em>niʿmati l-bidʿatu hādhihi</em> — what an excellent innovation this is") and elaborated by Imam al-Shāfiʿī, distinguishes between <em>bidʿah ḍalāla</em> (a religiously blameworthy innovation that contradicts the Sharīʿah) and <em>bidʿah ḥasana</em> (a praiseworthy innovation that gathers people around already-legislated acts, such as building madrasas or printing the Qurʾān). The classical five-category taxonomy of innovation — obligatory, recommended, permissible, offensive, and unlawful — developed by al-ʿIzz ibn ʿAbd al-Salām and confirmed by Imam al-Nawawī and Ibn Ḥajar al-ʿAsqalānī, is treated in the appendix "Blameworthy Innovation (Bidʿa)" in Imam al-Nawawī's <em>al-Maqāṣid</em> (Sh. Nuh Keller's translation and notes, pp. 154–156).</p>

  <p class="term"><strong>ʿAqīdah</strong> — Creed. The doctrinal positions a Muslim is required to affirm: oneness of God, prophethood, the unseen, the resurrection, the divine attributes. Sunnī Islam from the 4th Hijri century onward developed two systematic creedal schools: the <strong>Ashʿarī</strong> (after Imam Abū al-Ḥasan al-Ashʿarī, d. 324 AH) and the <strong>Māturīdī</strong> (after Imam Abū Manṣūr al-Māturīdī, d. 333 AH). Both are recognized as orthodox by the four madhāhib of fiqh; Ḥanafīs are typically Māturīdī, Shāfiʿīs and Mālikīs are typically Ashʿarī, and Ḥanbalīs vary. The Salafī movement rejects the dialectical-theology methodology of both schools and advocates an "Atharī" or text-based creed that hews to literal readings of the divine attributes.</p>

  <p class="term"><strong>Ijmāʿ</strong> — Consensus. The unanimous agreement of the qualified scholars of a generation on a religious question. Disputed in scope but accepted as a source of legal authority by all four madhāhib. The classical Sunnī argument frequently rests on ijmāʿ ("the four madhāhib have permitted X for fourteen centuries"); the Salafī reply is typically to dispute that the relevant ijmāʿ exists or is binding. For the classical definition and evidentiary basis — including the Qurʾānic grounding in Q 4:59 and Q 4:115 and the prophetic ḥadīth "My Community shall not agree on an error" — see the appendix "Scholarly Consensus (Ijmāʿ)" in Imam al-Nawawī's <em>al-Maqāṣid</em> (Sh. Nuh Keller's translation and notes, pp. 152–153).</p>

  <p class="term"><strong>Taqlīd</strong> — Following a qualified scholar. Linguistically, "putting a collar on" — accepting a ruling on the authority of someone qualified to derive it. The classical Sunnī position is that any Muslim who is not a fully-qualified <em>mujtahid</em> must do taqlīd of a recognized madhhab; this is the position of all four schools and the basis of the maḏhab system. The Salafī methodological position rejects systematic taqlīd of a single madhhab in favour of "following the strongest evidence" — a position that classical scholars argue requires the very ijtihād-level training the Salafī claimant typically lacks. Imam al-Nawawī treats this at length in <em>al-Maqāṣid</em> (with Sh. Nuh Keller's appendix "Why Muslims Follow Madhhabs"); the appendix lays out the structural reasons the classical Sunnī tradition holds taqlīd of a recognised madhhab to be the default obligation for the non-mujtahid.</p>

  <p class="term"><strong>Ta'wīl</strong> — Interpretive reading. In ʿaqīdah, the technique by which mutashābih (ambiguous) verses about Allāh's "hand", "face", "throne", or "descent" are read as figurative or attributed to Allāh's knowledge alone, rather than read literally. The Ashʿarī and Māturīdī schools accept ta'wīl in cases where literal reading would imply anthropomorphism (<em>tashbīh</em>) or corporealism (<em>tajsīm</em>); the Salafī position is broadly literalist (the verses are affirmed "without how" — <em>bilā kayf</em> — but in their apparent meaning).</p>

  <p class="term"><strong>Kalām</strong> — Dialectical theology. The discipline of using rational argument to defend Islamic creedal claims, originating in the late 2nd/early 3rd Hijri century in response to philosophical and inter-religious challenges. The Ashʿarī and Māturīdī schools are kalām schools. The Salafī position holds kalām to be an illegitimate innovation; classical Sunnism holds it to be a permitted (and often obligatory) instrument when the alternative is leaving philosophical and rationalist challenges to the religion unanswered.</p>

  <p class="term"><strong>Tawassul</strong> — Seeking nearness. Asking Allāh by means of someone or something He has honoured — by His names and attributes (universally accepted), by one's own good deeds (universally accepted), or by the rank of the Prophet ﷺ or a righteous person (the disputed case, accepted by the four madhāhib, restricted by the Salafī position).</p>

  <p class="term"><strong>Istighātha</strong> — Calling for help. Distinguished from tawassul: tawassul is asking Allāh <em>through</em> someone, istighātha is calling on someone to ask Allāh on one's behalf. The four madhāhib distinguish istighātha from worship by intention and the One actually being asked; the Salafī position generally treats istighātha addressed to a non-living person as shirk.</p>

  <p class="term"><strong>Madhhab</strong> — School of jurisprudence. The four canonical Sunnī madhāhib are the Ḥanafī (after Imam Abū Ḥanīfa, d. 150 AH), the Mālikī (after Imam Mālik ibn Anas, d. 179 AH), the Shāfiʿī (after Imam Muḥammad ibn Idrīs al-Shāfiʿī, d. 204 AH), and the Ḥanbalī (after Imam Aḥmad ibn Ḥanbal, d. 241 AH). Each consists of a body of derivations and rulings transmitted through unbroken scholarly chains; an ordinary Muslim follows one of them as their methodological framework.</p>

  <p class="term"><strong>Salaf vs. "Salafī"</strong> — The lowercase <em>salaf</em> means "predecessor" — the first three generations of Muslims (Ṣaḥāba, Tābiʿīn, Tabaʿ al-Tābiʿīn), whose authority every Sunnī school accepts. Capitalised "Salafī" or "Salafism" refers to the modern revivalist movement that began with Muḥammad ibn ʿAbd al-Wahhāb in 18th-century Najd and was globalised through 20th-century Saudi institutions. The two are distinct: the Salaf are a generation; Salafism is a school of thought that claims to recover their methodology directly. The <a href="/">Origins page</a> sketches the latter's history.</p>

  <h3 id="scope">What this site is not</h3>
  <p>Dār al-Ḥaqq is not a fatwa platform. The maintainer is a student of traditional Sunnī ʿilm, not a muftī, and the site does not issue rulings. The topic pages organize and frame existing scholarship; for binding answers on personal practice, ask a qualified shaykh in your locality.</p>

  <p>It is also not a comprehensive treatment of every contested question — the topic list is a small starter set, not a survey. The <a href="/sources">Sources page</a> lists the answer-sites we draw on most, and the topic pages cite books (Imam al-Nawawī's <em>al-Adhkār</em>, al-Suyūṭī's <em>Ḥusn al-Maqṣid</em>, al-Ṭabarānī's <em>al-Muʿjam al-Kabīr</em>, and others) where they are the primary basis of an argument.</p>

  <h3 id="tone">Tone and standards</h3>
  <p>Every quotation must be verbatim from a verifiable source. We do not paraphrase scholars in their own quotation marks; we do not insert words into a citation that the cited scholar did not write. We do not use pejoratives or labels intended to delegitimize a scholarly opponent (<em>mubtadiʿ</em>, <em>ḍāll</em>, etc.) — the position is named, the position is argued, the reader is trusted to draw conclusions. Where we cannot verify a quote at the cited source, we drop it. Where a topic page would be misleading without a particular citation we can't locate, we acknowledge the limitation rather than fabricate.</p>
